AB  - Many children who experience parental divorce are found to lack confidence in their adult romantic relationships. The current study utilized a quantitative research design to look at specific factors contributing to this lack of relationship confidence. Individuals participated in an online survey assessing relationship confidence and co-parenting abilities by their parents. The study looked at positive co-parenting, negative co-parenting, gender, age at time of divorce, educational level and relationship status as possible factors regarding lack of relationship confidence. Despite the initial hypotheses not being supported, further results were congruent with previous literature indicating that when positive aspects of co-parenting are displayed, more positive aspects are elevated and negative aspects actually decrease. Also, results showed that women's reports of being exposed to conflict were significant over males, which is also congruent with previous literature. These results would be beneficial to incorporate into Massachusetts's mandatory class that divorcing individuals with minor children have to take in order to inform parents of the effects of co-parenting during the divorce process. This information could assist in breaking the vicious cycle of divorce that can be present in families. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
