AB  - The purpose of this grounded theory study was to explore the perceptions and experiences of the paternal parent with regard to how his paternal role changed from being a custodial, residential parent to that of non-residential, non-custodial parent after a divorce. The barriers encountered when trying to remain involved in his child(ren)'s lives were also analyzed. Of particular interest is the father's role and involvement in the academic success, behavior, and social and emotional development of the child(ren) after the dissolution of a marriage. The following questions guided the study: (a) How do non-residential fathers perceive their child(ren)'s post life after the dissolution of a marriage? (b) How do non-residential fathers influence their child(ren)'s academic life? (c) How do non-residential fathers influence their child(ren)'s behavior and social/emotional life? (d) What barriers do non-residential fathers face when trying to remain involved in their child(ren)'s lives? The participants of the student were divorced, non-residential, non-custodial fathers with school aged children under the age of 18. The children attended one of the seven feeder elementary schools to Tesseract High School and one attended Tesseract High School. The participants were divorced less than three years. Data was collected through semi-structured interviews and a focus group. The participants of this study shared a variety of information. It was revealed that the children of the fathers of this study adjusted well after the divorce. None of the participants revealed significant negative issues with regard to their children's academic success, behavior, and social/emotional development as a result of the father becoming at least part-time non-residential. The participants confirmed many of the barriers that the review of the literature found to remaining involved in their children's lives post-divorce. This study confirmed that the better the relationship is between the mother and father post-divorce, the happier the father is with his involvement with his children. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
