AB  - Prior investigations have explored the association between divorce and various outcomes to examine the best interests of youth experiencing parental divorce. Investigated variables associated with the impact of divorce on youth included inter-parental conflict, post-divorce parenting, and level of parental involvement post-divorce. Research suggested that these factors may be related to changes in the areas of self-esteem, and life satisfaction for emerging adults who experienced parental divorce. The purpose of this study was to re-examine these variables in the context of new legal presumptions towards shared parenting and the creation of parenting plans. Specifically, a new residential calendar was utilized to quantify the amount of time spent with each parent and the number of transitions between homes that were experienced. These variables are examined to test their associations with self-esteem and life satisfaction, while controlling for inter-parental conflict and parenting style. Statistically significant results are found for the role of parental support on self-esteem and life satisfaction. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
