AB  - Children have long been excluded from the conversations surrounding their custody arrangements, a large decision that will greatly affect their well-being. Children are frequently uninvolved in court-mediated custody arrangements, as judges do not typically involve children in this decision until the end. Even when included in the process, their voices are not sought until a certain age or maturity level, and young children's voices are rarely ever sought. As such, this dissertation aimed to understand the experiences of six emerging adults who experienced dissatisfaction with their custody arrangements. This dissertation adopted a qualitative descriptive case study method and interviewed individuals age 18 through 27 who experienced parental separation or divorce under the age of 13 and who experienced dissatisfaction with their custody arrangements. Through the use of analytic memos and systematic coding of transcribed interviews, themes indicated that their dissatisfaction surrounded poor parent-child relationships after the separation, added responsibilities beyond the scope of their developmental age, a loss of stability, and a feeling that the family has been broken. Additionally, the participants felt that they struggled with the effects of their parents' separation into adulthood. The findings imply that potential solutions to addressing children's dissatisfaction with their custody arrangements should target the betterment of parent-child relationships post separation, as well as the collaboration between mental health professionals and family law professionals. Several recommendations are provided for parents, mental health professionals, and family law professionals. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
