AB  - Divorce is highly prevalent in the United States with approximately 3.2 out of every 1,000 marriages ending in divorce each year (Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, 2014). Divorce impacts both children and parents. Previous research suggests that children demonstrate better adjustment when their parents develop and maintain a cooperative co-parenting relationship (Beckmeyer, Coleman, & Ganong, 2014). Hostile Attribution Bias is the tendency to interpret the intention of others as hostile when social contextual cues are ambiguous (Epps & Kendall, 1995). It is believed that a hostile attribution bias will reduce quality of co-parenting, but that this relation will be moderated by forgiveness. The purpose of this study was to explore the relation in parents among empathy, forgiveness, and hostile attribution bias that contributes to effective co-parenting and resulting child outcomes, and examine the differences that dispositional forgiveness or forgiveness of an ex-spouse contribute to these relations. The inclusion criteria for participants was being divorced between 1 and 7 years and having at least one child under the age of 18. Participants filled out self-report measures on a common source survey system assessing for level of forgiveness, empathy, post-divorce quality of co-parenting, and child adjustment. Hostile attribution bias was measured with vignettes (both ambiguous and hostile) depicting email scenarios that are relevant to co-parenting. A total of 126 participants were surveyed. It was hypothesized that parents who rate themselves as higher in forgiveness would be more effective co-parents. It was also expected that parents who rate themselves higher in forgiveness would have children with lower internalizing and externalizing behaviors. Forgiveness was predicted to moderate the relation between a hostile attribution bias and child behavior as well as the relation between hostile attribution bias and co-parenting. Finally, empathy was predicted to moderate the relation between forgiveness and hostile attribution bias, such that higher levels of empathy would foster forgiveness. Pearson correlations and hierarchical regression with moderation analyses were used to test these hypotheses. Parents who rated themselves as having more dispositional forgiveness as well as more forgiveness of their ex-spouses were found to have significantly better quality of co-parenting. Level of forgiveness was not found to be related to interpreting ambiguous vignettes as less hostile nor did it moderate the relation between a hostile attribution bias and child behavior or hostile attribution bias and quality of co-parenting. Parents who rated themselves as more empathetic did interpret closed ended questions as less hostile, but not opened ended. In addition, empathy was not found to moderate the relation between forgiveness and a hostile attribution bias for open ended questions measuring hostility, however, it was found to moderate the relation for closed ended questions. Clinical implications, limitations of the present study, and directions for future research were discussed. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
