AB  - In many Western countries, shared-time parenting after separation is emerging as a new family form. This development has been accompanied by an intensification of research into risks and benefits for children. Separated parents with shared-time arrangements tend to report that their children are doing well and that they and their children like the arrangements, but shared parenting itself does not appear to cause this desirable situation. Instead, recent studies continue to suggest that well-functioning families are more likely to select into shared-time parenting. Consistent with many early US studies, the latest international research suggests that children can benefit from shared-time arrangements postseparation. But these arrangements can also involve risks for children—particularly when children are very young, the arrangements are inflexible and unresponsive to the needs of the child, there is uncontrolled parental conflict, mothers report ongoing safety concerns, or there is some combination of these factors. In this chapter we (a) discuss the conceptual, measurement and sampling issues that continue to make shared-time research an imperfect science, (b) summarize key findings from the latest studies of shared-time arrangements examining child outcomes, (b) set out the strengths and limitations of each study, and (c) suggest five broad domains to consider in determining whether shared-time arrangements will benefit children or put them at risk.
